  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved over several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) efforts emerged in the 1970s\n- Bank Secrecy Act of 1970 in the United States was an early landmark legislation\n- Focused on requiring financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n\n2. International Development:\n- 1988 Vienna Convention against illicit drug trafficking introduced international framework\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989 to develop global AML standards\n- Promoted international cooperation and standardized regulatory approaches\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 criminalized money laundering\n- 1990 European Community Directive on money laundering\n- USA PATRIOT Act of 2001 significantly expanded AML regulations\n\n4. Expanding Scope:\n- Initially focused on drug trafficking proceeds\n- Gradually expanded to cover terrorism financing, tax evasion, and other criminal activities\n- Increased reporting requirements and due diligence obligations for financial institutions\n\n5. Modern Regulatory Landscape:\n- Increasingly sophisticated global regulatory frameworks\n- Enhanced technological monitoring and reporting mechanisms\n- Continued adaptation to emerging financial technologies and criminal methods\n\nEach jurisdiction has developed its own specific legal approach, but international standards have become increasingly harmonized.",
